"Eppich B., Dede L., Ferenczy A., Garamvölgyi Á., Horváth L., Isépy I., Priszter Sz., Hufnagel L.","Climatic effects on the phenology of geophytes",2010,"Applied Ecology and Environmental Research","7","3",,"253","266",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-76849084885&partnerID=40&md5=e7f1400cae279ba10a746f7264b78283","Department of Mathematics and Informatics, Corvinus University of Budapest, Faculty of Horticulture, Villányi út 29-43, H-1118 Budapest, Hungary; 'Adaptation to Climate Change' Research Group, Hungarian Academy of Sciences, Office for Subsidised Research Units, Villányi út 29-43, H-1118 Budapest, Hungary; Botanical Garden, Eötvös Loránd University, Faculty of Science, Illés utca 25, H-1083 Budapest, Hungary","Eppich, B., Department of Mathematics and Informatics, Corvinus University of Budapest, Faculty of Horticulture, Villányi út 29-43, H-1118 Budapest, Hungary; Dede, L., Department of Mathematics and Informatics, Corvinus University of Budapest, Faculty of Horticulture, Villányi út 29-43, H-1118 Budapest, Hungary; Ferenczy, A., Department of Mathematics and Informatics, Corvinus University of Budapest, Faculty of Horticulture, Villányi út 29-43, H-1118 Budapest, Hungary; Garamvölgyi, Á., Department of Mathematics and Informatics, Corvinus University of Budapest, Faculty of Horticulture, Villányi út 29-43, H-1118 Budapest, Hungary; Horváth, L., 'Adaptation to Climate Change' Research Group, Hungarian Academy of Sciences, Office for Subsidised Research Units, Villányi út 29-43, H-1118 Budapest, Hungary; Isépy, I., Botanical Garden, Eötvös Loránd University, Faculty of Science, Illés utca 25, H-1083 Budapest, Hungary; Priszter, Sz., Botanical Garden, Eötvös Loránd University, Faculty of Science, Illés utca 25, H-1083 Budapest, Hungary; Hufnagel, L., 'Adaptation to Climate Change' Research Group, Hungarian Academy of Sciences, Office for Subsidised Research Units, Villányi út 29-43, H-1118 Budapest, Hungary","Nowadays, the scientific and social significance of the research of climatic effects has become outstanding. In order to be able to predict the ecological effects of the global climate change, it is necessary to study monitoring databases of the past and explore connections. For the case study mentioned in the title, historical weather data series from the Hungarian Meteorological Service and Szaniszló Priszter's monitoring data on the phenology of geophytes have been used. These data describe on which days the observed geophytes budded, were blooming and withered. In our research we have found that the classification of the observed years according to phenological events and the classification of those according to the frequency distribution of meteorological parameters show similar patterns, and the one variable group is suitable for explaining the pattern shown by the other one. Furthermore, our important result is that the dates of all three observed phenophases correlate significantly with the average of the daily temperature fluctuation in the given period. The second most often significant parameter is the number of frosty days, this also seem to be determinant for all phenophases. Usual approaches based on the temperature sum and the average temperature don't seem to be really important in this respect. According to the results of the research, it has turned out that the phenology of geophytes can be well modelled with the linear combination of suitable meteorological parameters. © 2009, Penkala Bt., Budapest, Hungary.","Climate change; Cluster analysis; Correlation; Meteorology; Phenological models; Phenophases",,,,,,,"Bruns, E., Chmielewski, F.-M., van Vliet, A.J.H., The Global Phenological Monitoring Concept (2003) Phenology: An Integrative Environmental Science, , In: Schwartz, M.D. (ed.), Kluwer Academic Publishers, The Netherlands; Chen, X., East Asia (2003) Phenology: An Integrative Environmental Science, , In: Schwartz, M.D. (ed.), Kluwer Academic Publishers, The Netherlands;